Project Title: 

House Price Prediction using Machine Learning Algorithms 

 

1. Project Description 

House price prediction is a critical problem in the real estate industry, where accurate pricing models help buyers, sellers, and financial institutions make informed decisions. This project develops a predictive model that estimates house prices based on features such as area, location, building type, condition, and the number of rooms. Machine learning algorithms are applied to identify the most influential factors and provide reliable price predictions. 

2. Learning Objectives 

Understand and apply regression modeling techniques. 

Perform exploratory data analysis (EDA) and feature engineering. 

Compare multiple regression models and evaluate performance metrics. 

 

3. Timeline 

Start Date: Sept 7, 2025 

Deadline: Sept 14, 2025 

4. Algorithm Used 

Multiple Linear Regression (Baseline): Captures linear relationships between features and house prices. 

Support Vector Regression (SVR): Captures complex relationships by fitting data within a defined margin. 

Random Forest Regressor: An ensemble approach that averages predictions from multiple decision trees for better generalization. 

5. Tools & Libraries 

Python 

Pandas, NumPy → Data manipulation 

Matplotlib, Seaborn → Data visualization 

Scikit-learn → Machine learning models, preprocessing, and evaluation 

6. Dataset Description 

Source: HousePricePrediction.xlsx (Kaggle-style dataset) 

Size: 13 features, ~1,000+ records 

Target Variable: SalePrice (house price in USD) 

Key Features: 

LotArea → Lot size (sq. ft.) 

MSZoning → Zoning classification 

BldgType → Type of dwelling 

OverallCond → House condition rating 

YearBuilt → Construction year 

TotalBsmtSF → Basement size 

Exterior1st → Exterior covering type 

7. Methodology 

Data Preprocessing: 

Dropped irrelevant column: Id 

Handled missing values (SalePrice filled with mean, others dropped) 

Applied OneHotEncoder for categorical variables (MSZoning, LotConfig, BldgType, Exterior1st) 

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): 

Heatmap for correlation between numerical features 

Barplots for categorical feature distributions 

Unique category counts visualized 

Model Training: 

Split dataset: 80% training, 20% validation 

Models tested: SVR, Random Forest, Multiple Linear Regression 

Evaluation Metrics: 

Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) 

Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) 

R² Score 

8. Results 

